Peripatetic Critolaus, is left unmentioned here and in Plutarch, Cato M. 22, 1. The date, 155 B.c.‚ marks an epoeh in the attitude of the Roman nobility towards Greek philosophy. An earlier trace of the new influence is indicated by the S.C. of 161 B.C.‚ which banished Gk philo- sophy and teachers of rhetoric from Rome. The residence of the thousand Achaeans in Italy, from 168 B.C. onwards, no doubt helped to prepare the way for the effect produced by the embassy. For the circumstances that gave occasion for the sending of the legation see Momms. H.R. iv 199. The Athenians had plun- dered Oropus and, when condemned by the Sicyonium, whom the Romans had appointed arbitrators‚ to pay a fine of 500 talents, appealed to Rome.
